solutions.content:
Initially, the idea is to check the number of disconnected islands. If the count of such islands is NOT 1, then there would be no need to convert a land cell into a water cell to further disconnect the islands. In such cases, we return 0.

Now, if there happens to be exactly 1 island in the grid, we convert each land cell into a water cell and check if the main island can be disintegrated into two or more smaller islands. If it is possible, by breaking any such land cell, we return 1.

In all the other cases, it would require (at max) 2 land cells (to be converted to water cells) to break up the main island. In this case, we return 2 :)

Proof of the last statement: A single disconnected land cell is also an island. Keeping this in mind, in order to break up an island into two (or more islands), we can make a corner land cell disconnected by converting two adjoining land cells into water cells.


**C++ Code:**


