# Approach
-> Fix the root and then think about combinations.
-> Every node has two sides; left and right
-> At the top most level, we cannot change the order ordering among the left side elements or the right side elements, but we can change the ordering of how a combination of these left side and right side element is present.
```
-> For eg: [3,4,5,1,2]
-> root is 3
-> Left side: [1,2]
-> Right side: [4,5]
-> Now we cant change the ordering among (1 and 2) and (4 and 5)
-> But we can change between their combination (1,2,4,5), (1,4,2,5), (4,5,1,2) etc.
```

-> For each node we will see combinations this way i.e. left side and right side.
-> With some observation you'll understand that if the number of elements on the right side is denoted by `l[node]` and right side `r[node]`, there can be a total of 

$$\Large~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~{l[node]+r[node]-1 \choose l[node]} + {l[node]+r[node]-1 \choose r[node]}$$ 


combinations are possible corresponding to this node. 
***[** ASK IF YOU DON'T UNDERSTAND THIS, I CAN EXPLAIN WITH A DIAGRAM **]***


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n^2)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

