# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

As many other solutions have already explained, the number of ways can be calculated using *recursive combinations*. Given the tree structure:
```
NumberOfWays(node) = Choose(left_node_size + right_node_size, left_size) *
    NumberOfWays(left_node) * NumberOfWays(right_node);
```
The *node_size* above means the size of the substree starting at that node. We will use this expression throughout below.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

The key here is the `n choose k` combinatoric number, which is `n!/(k!(n-k)!)`, or in our case
```
(left_node_size + right_node_size)! / (left_node_size!right_node_size!)
```
It is not easy to calculate factorial efficiently, so if we use a **math trick to optimize** it.

Note that the size of tree starting this node is `left_node_size + right_node_size + 1`, we can transform our initial formula:

```
NumberOfWays(node) = 
    (left_node_size + right_node_size)! / (left_node_size!right_node_size!) *
    NumberOfWays(left_node) * NumberOfWays(right_node)
  = this_node_size! / (left_node_size!right_node_size!) / this_node_size *
    NumberOfWays(left_node) * NumberOfWays(right_node);
  = ... // recursively expands all sub nodes
  = this_node_size!/ (\Prod_{all node} node_size)
```
`\Prod_{all node} node size` means to multiple all *node_size* together, for each node.
Basically we managed to cancel all factorial except one. We got **only one** factorial to calculate and a bunch of denominators to divide.

For the factorial, we simply multiply each number and immediately do th mod to reduce the size of the number to prevent overflow.
For the divsion, we can use efficient [modular inverse algorithm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multiplicative_inverse) since `10^9 + 7` is a prime number. Here we choose extended euclid algorithm.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Worse case $$\Theta(N^2)$$, average $$\Theta(N \log N)$$
The worse case part only happens in the "tree building" process, for the actually calculation this is always O(N logN). The logN comes from the extended euclid algorith, while the outer post order tree visit is linear.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$\Theta(N)$$

# Code
```
namespace {

constexpr int kMod = 1000'000'007;

// REQUIRES: a >=0, b >= 0
int ExtendedEuclid(int a, int b, int& x, int& y) {
  if (a < b) {
    swap(a, b);
  }
  int xa = 1;
  int xb = 0;
  int ya = 0;
  int yb = 1;
  while (b > 0) {
    auto r = std::div(a, b);
    a = b;
    b = r.rem;
    xa -= xb * r.quot;
    swap(xa, xb);
    ya -= yb * r.quot;
    swap(ya, yb); 
  }
  x = xa;
  y = ya;
  return a;
}

// Requires that P is a prime and 2P < int32max
template <int P>
class Num {
 public:
  Num(int v) : v_(v) {}

  Num operator+(Num n) const {
    return (v_ + n.v_) % P;
  }

  Num operator-(Num n) const {
    return (v_ - n.v_ + P) % P;
  }

  Num operator*(Num n) const {
    return static_cast<int64_t>(v_) * n.v_ % P;
  }

  Num operator/(Num n) const {
    return (*this) * n.Inverse();
  }

  Num Inverse() const {
    int x = 0;
    int y = 0;
    ExtendedEuclid(P, v_, x, y);  // Must be 1
    return (y + P) % P;
  }

  int value() const {
    return v_;
  }

 private:
  int v_;
};

template <int P>
std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& s, Num<P> n) {
  return s << n.value();
}

using Number = Num<kMod>;

struct Node {
  int value;
  int left;
  int right;

  Node(int value) : value(value), left(-1), right(-1) {}
};

void Insert(vector<Node>& nodes, int num) {
  if (nodes.empty()) {
    nodes.push_back(num);
    return;
  }
  int index = 0;
  int prev_index = -1;
  while (index != -1) {
    Node& node = nodes[index];
    prev_index = index;
    if (node.value < num) {
      index = node.right;
    } else {
      index = node.left;
    }
  }
  Node& p = nodes[prev_index];
  (p.value < num ? p.right : p.left) = nodes.size();
  nodes.push_back(num);
}

int TreeSize(const vector<Node>& nodes, int index, Number& ways) {
  if (index == -1) {
    return 0;
  }
  int left = TreeSize(nodes, nodes[index].left, ways);
  int right = TreeSize(nodes, nodes[index].right, ways);
  int total = 1 + left + right;
  // cout << "[" << index << "] " << total << endl;
  // cout << "    " << ways;
  ways = ways / total;
  // cout << " => " << ways << endl;
  return total;
}

}  // namespace

class Solution {
public:
  int numOfWays(vector<int>& nums) {
    const int N = nums.size();
    vector<Node> nodes;
    nodes.reserve(N);
    for (int num : nums) {
      Insert(nodes, num);
    }
    Number ways = 1;
    for (int i = 1; i <= N; ++i) {
      ways = ways * i;
    }
    // cout << "N! = " << ways << endl;
    TreeSize(nodes, 0, ways);
    return (ways - 1).value();
  }
};
```

